# BFF Auth-Flow Invariants

## Tokens live in httpOnly cookies only

NEVER store access tokens, refresh tokens, or session identifiers in `localStorage`, `sessionStorage`, or any JS-accessible client state.
ALWAYS set tokens via `cookies()` (Server Action / Route Handler) with `httpOnly: true`, `sameSite: "lax"`, `secure: true`.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – token written server-side, never reachable from JS
import { cookies } from "next/headers";

cookies().set("access_token", tokenResponse.access_token, {
  httpOnly: true,
  sameSite: "lax",
  secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production",
  path: "/",
});

// ❌ BAD – exposes token to any JS on the page
localStorage.setItem("access_token", tokenResponse.access_token);
```

## `OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET` is server-only — no `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix

NEVER expose `OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET` or `OAUTH_CLIENT_ID` under a `NEXT_PUBLIC_` name.
ALWAYS access them as bare `process.env.OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET` / `process.env.OAUTH_CLIENT_ID` inside Server Actions, Route Handlers, or `src/lib/` modules that are never imported by Client Components.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – read only on the server
const secret = process.env.OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET; // defined without NEXT_PUBLIC_

// ❌ BAD – would be bundled into the client
const secret = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET;
```

## All authenticated Drupal calls go through `drupalFetch` server-side

NEVER call `fetch(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL, ...)` directly from a Client Component or with a bare token string.
ALWAYS use a `drupalFetch` helper (in `src/lib/drupal.ts` or similar) that:
1. Reads the `access_token` cookie via `cookies()`.
2. Attaches `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on the server.
3. Is called only from Server Components, Server Actions, or Route Handlers.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – drupalFetch used inside a Server Component
import { drupalFetch } from "@/lib/drupal";

export default async function ProductPage() {
  const data = await drupalFetch("/jsonapi/node/product");
  return <pre>{JSON.stringify(data)}</pre>;
}

// ❌ BAD – token read from client state and fetch made from a Client Component
"use client";
const token = localStorage.getItem("access_token");
const res = await fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL}/jsonapi/node/product`, {
  headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` },
});
```

## Credential exchange happens only in Server Actions or Route Handlers

NEVER POST OAuth credentials (`client_id`, `client_secret`, username, password) from a Client Component.
ALWAYS perform the token exchange inside:
- A Server Action (`"use server"` function), or
- A Route Handler (`app/api/**/route.ts`).

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – credential exchange in a Server Action
"use server";
import { cookies } from "next/headers";

export async function login(formData: FormData) {
  const res = await fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL}/oauth/token`, {
    method: "POST",
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      grant_type: "password",
      client_id: process.env.OAUTH_CLIENT_ID!,
      client_secret: process.env.OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET!,
      username: formData.get("username") as string,
      password: formData.get("password") as string,
    }),
  });
  const token = await res.json();
  cookies().set("access_token", token.access_token, { httpOnly: true, sameSite: "lax" });
}

// ❌ BAD – credentials sent from the browser
"use client";
await fetch("/oauth/token", {
  method: "POST",
  body: JSON.stringify({ client_secret: "5R83e1ur9i4z", ... }),
});
```

## Summary checklist

| Concern | Rule |
|---|---|
| Token storage | `httpOnly` cookie only — never `localStorage` |
| `OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET` | No `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix — server env only |
| Drupal API calls | Via `drupalFetch` server-side only |
| OAuth exchange | Server Action or Route Handler only |
